arch:property.oc:show_val: Main construction of the Bath Complex.

Phase VI: Late Nabataean pre CE 106 minor collapses and repairs. Probable early collapse of the Baroque Room and damage occurs in both the Anteroom and Shrine Room. The tabun in Room A is used to store CE 1st c. Nabataean fine wares. East 'Cistern" used as a dump. Bath Complex built.

Locus 28 is the ledge on which the columns (Locus 27) and intercolumnar walls (Loci 9, 74, and 75) of the ‘colonnaded corridor’ rest. It is not fully exposed, and is only fully visible to the east, below the east columns of Locus 27 and Locus 9. In this area, the floor has been robbed out, making the 8 cm height of the ledge noticeable, whereas it is flush with the floor to the west. This would suggest then that this is not necessarily a ledge, but rather a continuation of the floor (Locus 72). As it exists under the columns as well though, and for the sake of caution, it has been differentiated from the floor locus. The pavers of the ledge are hewn sandstone, with one row visible. Contemporaneous with the first construction of the ‘colonnaded corridor,’ this locus is phased to Stage 2.
